flowRoot.flowPara: Weighing between 0.1 and 8 solar masses, they make up 97% of the stars in our Universe.
They spend most of their lives burning hydrogen in their core, follwed by helium.
As they age and exhaust their fuel, they expand and cool, becoming Red Giant Stars.
The combination of powerful stellar winds and bloating causes the ejection of the stellar envelope.
The enriched star material is returned to interstellar space in a Planetary Neblua, leaving behind the dead stellar core:
